/* ===========================================================================
   DASH Module — Test Accessory               |  module type: ACCESSORY
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
   This is a REFERENCE DASH module, written to be read — same discipline as
   the steering wheel SYSTEM module. Nothing here uses access a community
   builder couldn't have (the DASH "SDKable" principle).

   WHAT THIS MODULE IS
     A bench-test ACCESSORY module. ACCESSORY modules own an agnostic
     interactive panel and ship visual assets to DASH at install time. This
     one exists for exactly one purpose: to prove DASH's ACCESSORY install
     path (roadmap 1.4.4) end to end on real hardware —

         MANIFEST -> BLOCK (raw bytes) -> BLOCK (raw bytes) -> INSTALL_END

     It ships THREE assets, chosen so the transfer test earns its keep:
       1. icon             — an SVG gauge face (multi-line text)
       2. panel_background — a REAL binary PNG (a little gauge tile)
       3. panel_layout     — arduino.md §11's *provisional* test layout
                             format, tying the background + overlays together
     The PNG is the important one: its bytes include nulls, pipes, CRs and
     newlines, so it proves DASH's length-prefixed framing is genuinely
     binary-safe — not merely tolerant of text with line breaks. The layout
     is arbitrary test content (the real panel spec, §11, is not locked) and
     DASH renders nothing at install anyway — it receives, CRC-checks, and
     stores. The finish line is DASH's Module Management screen: DISCOVER
     shows an ACCESSORY chip, INSTALL runs a determinate progress bar, the
     pane turns green, and DETAILS lists all three assets with the right
     byte counts.

     v2 (2026-07-07) — a second purpose, added once DASH 1.4.6 gave modules
     a live ACTIVE state: while ACTIVE, the module sends three REPORT
     variables every two seconds (see LIVE TEST REPORTS below). DASH routes
     REPORT nowhere until roadmap 1.4.9, but the lines show on the Serial
     Monitor wire tap — so the reports starting is visible proof an
     ACTIVATE landed, and their stopping dead is visible proof of a
     DEACTIVATE. The v1 sketch had a single such REPORT, off by default.

   WHAT IT DELIBERATELY DOES NOT DO
     - No ACTION / TRIGGER traffic — DASH routes none of that until roadmap
       1.4.9+. (REPORT is the one exception since v2, above — sent to be
       *watched*, not routed.)
     - No SUBSCRIBE lines — an ACCESSORY may subscribe (arduino.md §11), but
       keeping this sketch pure-accessory keeps the test unambiguous.
     - No variables / interactive-controls declarations — their install
       framing is an open item (arduino.md §10); per the 1.4.4 settlement an
       ACCESSORY install carries MANIFEST + BLOCKs only.

   THE WIRE  (arduino/arduino.md §1, §2, §8)
     Plain UTF-8 text, one message per line, pipe-separated positional
     fields — with ONE exception, and that exception is the whole point of
     this module: a BLOCK header line

         BLOCK|id|name|length|crc

     is followed by exactly `length` RAW BYTES. Those bytes are framed by
     the byte count alone — they may (and here deliberately DO) contain
     newlines, which DASH must read verbatim instead of line-splitting.
     After the last byte, normal line framing resumes immediately.

   THE CRC  (settled in DASH 1.4.4)
     CRC32 (the standard zip polynomial), sent as LOWERCASE HEXADECIMAL with
     no prefix and no padding — exactly what Arduino's String(crc, HEX)
     would produce. DASH parses the field base-16; a decimal CRC would fail
     every block and abort the install.

   TARGET BOARD
     Arduino Uno R4 WiFi (same bench board as the steering wheel module).
     Its USB Serial enumerates to the host as a CDC serial port, so this
     behaves exactly like a classic Uno R3.
   ===========================================================================*/

#include <string.h>   // strcmp — plain C string compare, no library needed

/* ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
   TRANSPORT SELECTION
   One ordinary Arduino Serial port. To run this exact code where the link to
   DASH is a UART instead, change ONE line to Serial1 — nothing else moves.
   --------------------------------------------------------------------------- */
#define DASH_SERIAL  Serial
#define DASH_BAUD    115200

/* ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
   MODULE IDENTITY  (arduino/arduino.md §3)
   Assigned id (the §3 no-MAC fallback), unique on this bench: the steering
   wheel module is ...EE01, so this one is ...EE02.
   --------------------------------------------------------------------------- */
const char* MODULE_ID = "0000DA58EE02";   // PLACEHOLDER assigned id — make it unique

/* ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
   IDENTITY TEXT  (sent in HELLO; field caps from arduino/arduino.md §10)
   --------------------------------------------------------------------------- */
const char* MODULE_TYPE = "ACCESSORY";               // exactly one type (§4a)
const char* MODULE_NAME = "Test Accessory";          // <= 24 chars
const char* MODULE_DESC = "Install path + live REPORT test module"; // <= 64
const char* MODULE_VERS = "v2.0";                    // <= 12 chars

/* ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
   THE TEST ASSETS
   Three blocks. The two text assets are multi-line ON PURPOSE, and the PNG
   is real binary — embedded newlines, nulls, pipe bytes and CRs are exactly
   what prove DASH's frame assembler reads a block payload verbatim by byte
   count, instead of line-splitting it. Content is otherwise arbitrary; DASH
   stores it, it does not render it yet.

   Real modules keep assets in flash and stream them out a chunk at a time,
   never holding a whole asset in RAM (§8). `const` arrays live in flash on
   this board; the chunked send in sendBlock() mirrors the streaming pattern.
   (On an AVR board you would add PROGMEM and pgm_read_byte — same idea.)
   --------------------------------------------------------------------------- */

